{{Infobox deity|venerated_in={{ill|Tateyama Shugen|WD=Q11597829|1=Tateyama Shugen}}}} [[File:20 Tateyama from Mikurigaike 1998-7-17.jpg|thumb|right|300px|View of {{ill|Tateyama|en|Tateyama|WD=Q364837|lt=Tateyama|1=Tateyama}} from {{ill|Mikurigaike|ja|ミクリガ池|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikurigaike|1=Mikurigaike|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11341916}}, with {{ill|8=ja|9=室堂小屋|Murodō Mountain Lodge|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/8=ja|1=Tateyama Murodō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11452988}} visible at the center-right]] '''Tateyama Gongen''' (立山権現) is a syncretic deity combining the {{ill|Mountain worship|en|Mountain worship|WD=Q93697439|lt=Mountain worship|1=Mountain worship}} of {{ill|Tateyama|en|Tateyama|WD=Q364837|lt=Tateyama|1=Tateyama}} with [[Shugendō]]. The deity's [[honji suijaku]] counterpart is [[Amitābha]].
== Overview == In the first year of {{ill|Taihō (era)|en|Taihō (era)|WD=Q1346269|lt=Taihō|1=Taihō (era)}} (701), during a falconry expedition on Tateyama, {{ill|Saeki no Arifusa|ja|佐伯有頼|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saeki no Arifusa|1=Saeki no Ariyori|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11382848}} (Jikō) encountered a miraculous bear believed to be an emanation of Amitābha. This encounter is considered the origin of Tateyama Gongen and marked the mountain's establishment as a sacred [[Shugendō]] site.<ref>''{{ill|Wakan Sansai Zue|en|Wakan Sansai Zue|WD=Q1135803|lt=Wakan Sansai Zue|1=Wakan Sansai Zue}}''.</ref>
On March 15 of the third year of Taihō (703), the Twelve Gongen deities manifested to the monk Kyōkō on Tateyama. They were subsequently enshrined as follows: the first shrine honors the deity of {{ill|Amitābha|ja|無量光仏|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amitābha|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 阿弥陀如来}} (Boundless Light Buddha), while the second through twelfth shrines correspond to various emanations, such as the Infinite Light Buddha, Unobstructed Light Buddha, Peerless Light Buddha, Flame King Light Buddha, Pure Light Buddha, Joyful Light Buddha, Wisdom Light Buddha, Unceasing Light Buddha, Inconceivable Light Buddha, Unspeakable Light Buddha, and the Transcending Sun and Moon Light Buddha.<ref>''[[Shintōshū]]'', "Tateyama Gongen Narrative."</ref>
In the {{ill|Edo period|en|Edo period|WD=Q184963|lt=Edo period|1=Edo period}}, the followers of Ashikura spread the worship of Tateyama Gongen throughout Japan.
== Separation of Shinto and Buddhism, and Haibutsu Kishaku == The [[Meiji Restoration]] brought about the [[Shinbutsu bunri|separation of Shinto and Buddhism]] and the [[Haibutsu kishaku|abolition of Buddhism]]. In 1869 (Meiji 2), the temples of {{ill|Ashikuraji|ja|芦峅寺|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashikuraji|1=Ashikuraji|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11614856}} and Iwakuraji were forced to close and reorganized into [[Oyama Shrine]]. Furthermore, the {{ill|Tateyama Shugendō|ja|立山修験|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tateyama Shugendō|1=Tateyama Shugen|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11597829}} rituals, such as the Nunobashi Grand Consecration, and the dissemination of Tateyama Gongen worship were prohibited.
